The world felt quiet a few days ago with Christine McVie passing. We love Fleetwood Mac, and the world losing a iconic woman like Christine reminds us how time really is fleeting, and we are now in a time where these influential musicians are getting older and leaving this realm. The music lives on making all these artists legends though. Music is an eternal force. Anyways. This album came out when I was 9 and it was very influential on me. All my friends were listening to Britney Spears and the Backstreet Boys… meanwhile I was crushing on Blink 182 and shamelessly in love with Avril Lavigne. I too am Canadian and every Canadian misfit girl in 2002 couldn’t ignore the effect Avril had. When the music video dropped for “Complicated” I wanted to wear Dickies, Skate, and be a Mallrat. I wanted to be one of the guys because I had trouble meeting girls I clicked with at that age. My older cousins who were in their teens listening to Rage Against the Machine would poke fun at me for idolizing this short pop punk princess, but my 9 year old ass didn’t care. She was real and authentic to me. She was a singer songwriter. My first concert was Avril on the next album “Under My Skin”. By the time high school came around her music became a guilty pleasure of childhood. I aged out of it, and she started singing about Hello Kitty and the songs started to sound like “pick-me girl” energy… I disconnected into new music phases. Indie Hipster shit took over and my “Let Go” CD went into a box of childhood memorabilia. Avril was like the movie “Garden State” to me… where I loved it when it came out but after a while it made me cringe. I read too many harsh reviews, had too many friends poke fun, and the lyrics only clicked with pubescence emotions. I finally dated the Sk8ter boy and he sucked ass. Whenever I walked into the shop today, and saw the 20th year anniversary it sort of gave me an existential crisis. I could feel the 9 year old inside me staring at the album that got me through childhood. I think everyone has an album like this in their life… this is my childhood guilty pleasure. There’s a point where you find a second wind, and fall in love with it all over again. You love it because it reminds you of a pure part of life.

This “production reflects a greater influence of styles such as industrial music and EBM, but maintaining the sound of analog synthesizers as a principle. The lyrics follow a concept based on the period of violence that Peru experienced in the 1980s, with samples of General Juan Velasco Alvarado and songs that refer to situations such as blackouts, bombings of terrorist groups, and the uncertainty of living in the midst of the armed conflict in a city lost in chaos. “
